metadata.name: Unknown Monuments #39
metadata.description:
That Monument belongs to someone.

.Four seasons of the year.
.Three Forest Densities.
.Nine monuments.
.Can be actived or inactive.
.Rare raining.

-

Monuments often seem peaceful,
Perhaps they bring mute regrets,
Maybe bloody words and gestures,
Perhaps even peace itself!

They are always rich and full of glory.
They always cry out to the history of a people

One of these days I'll build a monument.
Not a monument for what's great.
But a monumento for the misunderstood.
A monument of clay and blood.
A monument of old newspaper pieces,
A monument of bones and gold,
A monument covered in autumn leaves,
A damp monument,

Because it brings tears.

-

by Gen Doodler | twitter.com/GenDoodler

metadata.name: Gen DOS Punk #105
metadata.description:
Gen DOS Punks - A Generative Tribute to DOS Punks!

Each Punk is a unique 1/1.

222 fxrand() functions in total to ensure almost no duplicates whatsoever!

Features weren't included due to a technical limitation. However if you want to see those, you can check the console logs - they're all there!

You can also triple-tap on a phone or click S on your keyboard to perform a "right-click save as".

-----

And find the 'DOS Punks' creator on Twitter @maxcapacity

metadata.name: contrapuntos #326
metadata.description:
Musical counterpoint is to me an abstraction of the layered, intertwining rhythms of every activity we carry on in our lives. With a global tempo typically set in days, we fit all sorts of temporal structures where our joys and fears live and play out over the span of our lives. This series is a metaphorical transposition of the musical counterpoint into a visual space, sometimes with repeating patterns, sometimes with broken structures, sometimes isolated notes / hours / souls.

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, @msoriaro. Made with p5js & glsl.

metadata.name: Tezos Goons #346
metadata.description:
"When Humanity is in need, the Tezos Goons appear to fight the evil and aid the world..."


Tezos Goons is a pixel art PFP project that was created by the Greek Tezos community as a contribution to the collective effort to provide help for people affected by the devastating earthquake in Turkey and Syria through the #TezQuakeAid initiative. More info on the initiative can be found at https://app.joyn.xyz/contest/-tezquakeaid-gallery-a93c16832314

100% of the primary sales will go straight to the multi-sig contract that has been set up by @tezquakeaid and any royalties accumulated till the end of #TezQuakeAid will also be sent to the same contract to be used for the same cause.

"Tezos Goons" is a collective effort of the Tezos Greece community (https://twitter.com/Tezos_Gr).

The artwork of the project was created by the community member @MrEvdilos (https://twitter.com/MrEvdilos)

and the technical part was implemented by @mtsirides1 (https://twitter.com/mtsirides1) using @PureSpider's template. We thank them all for their kind contributions and their voluntary efforts!


For the Project:

Each Tezos Goon is randomly generated and has 7 traits (Background, Weapons, Bodies, Clothing, Mouth, Eyes, Headtop) from a total of 130 different options.

Another 6 "Legendary" animated Goons will be minted as a separate collection on Objkt and 5 of them will be given away to Tezos Goons holders through a raffle. Each goon that you mint (and hold) is 1 entry in the raffle. The 6th Legendary Goon will be auctioned for the same cause (#TezQualeAid).

metadata.name: System Œ≤ #169
metadata.description:
Œ± -> Œ≤ is about "Increases in magnitude and decreases in computation". And still related the fleeting time in the generating process.

My role in this work is more of a discoverer than a creator. 

Try to reveal the possibilities of time perception in the generative art through negotiating with incomprehensible mathematical equations.

What I want to explore through this work is that behind the generated results, the dynamic process of generations are equally diverse and unpredictable.

When we watch the generating process displayed on the computer, changing instantly, moving, multiplying, disappearing, and we hesitate, wonder, pause, await, as if many possibilities of time perception have emerged in the fragmented moments.

metadata.name: GRAPHEME #66
metadata.description:
Released on the occasion of the Tribute to Herbert W. Franke. 
www.tribute-hwf.com

‚ÄúOne criterion for art involves the process used by the artist for shaping the work. In the special case of mathematically supported fine art, the artmaking process occurs in a mathematically defined operation that allows the generation and transformation of images, methods used for picture processing.‚Äù - Herbert W. Franke

I first came across Franke‚Äôs ‚ÄòOrnamental Alphabets‚Äô in his book ùòäùò∞ùòÆùò±ùò∂ùòµùò¶ùò≥ ùòéùò≥ùò¢ùò±ùò©ùò™ùò§ùò¥ - ùòäùò∞ùòÆùò±ùò∂ùòµùò¶ùò≥ ùòàùò≥ùòµ, and was intrigued with the idea of using a simple letterform to explore different generative image processing techniques. 

I‚Äôve used letters and writing in my work for a long time, both with letterpress printing and in my asemic poetry programs. With asemic writing, I generate unrecognizable letters to reference text, and here I use recognizable letterforms removed from their typical function as language signifiers. 

My goal with this project was to build as much texture and layering as possible by warping and collaging the letters together in various ways. The font I‚Äôm using is a design I made years ago to supplement my wood type collection for printing. I really enjoyed being able to bring that part of my past work into my generative art practice. 

Each image is composed of the letters found in the hash for that piece, divided into either vowels or consonants. The program builds on a technique I‚Äôve used before, where I generate an image to an off-screen canvas and then dive through the pixels to pull out the color and form I want to surface in the final image.

25% of the primary sales will be donated on-chain to the Foundation Herbert W. Franke. These funds will be used by ZKM Karlsruhe to digitize Franke‚Äôs 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. Any additional funds raised will be donated to the R√ºtgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.

- Press ‚ÄúR‚Äù to increase the pixel density and reload the image (this can be render intensive and will create a really large file suitable for printing)
- Press ‚ÄúS‚Äù to save a copy

Made with p5js
Artist: Sarah Ridgley
October, 2022

metadata.name: RAUSCH #10
metadata.description:
RAUSCH is a series of generative artworks that explore imaginary digital architectures. 

This series challenges traditional notions of architectural representation and raises important questions about the role of resolution in design. Just as the pixel resolution of an image affects its perceived quality, the resolution of an architectural space can affect its qualities and livability. By embracing digital variation through codes, this series explores the interplay between abstract and concrete space through multiple resolutions. 

RAUSCH is inspired by the feeling of being overwhelmed by complex, chaotic and messy sensations, and aims to engage the viewer through a sense of wonder, disorientation, and awe.

Released on the occasion of Companions of Code, a group exhibition by VerticalCrypto Art at The NFT Gallery in London. 
Curated by Micol Ap. Exhibition 10-24 February 2023 

___________________________________________________
RAUSCH Controls:

Animation: 
‚Ä¢ ‚Äò1 - 2 - 3 - 4‚Äô animate views
‚Ä¢ 'MouseClick' pause/play animation

Functions:
(press key & wait)
‚Ä¢ 'F' 24 FPS
‚Ä¢ 'B' b/w mode 

Resize Canvas:
(press key & wait)
‚Ä¢ '6' Portrait A4 - 1000x1414
‚Ä¢ '7' Landscape 16:9 - 1920x1080
‚Ä¢ '8' Portrait 9:16 - 1080x1920
‚Ä¢ '9' Square 1:1 - 1024x1024
‚Ä¢ 'DoubleClick' Fullscreen

Save & Export Image:
‚Ä¢ 'S' save a .png of in current resolution

Save & Export GIF:
‚Ä¢ 'G' save a 1-2 sec. seamless loop .gif of current view 
‚Ä¢ 'P' save a 12-24 sec. seamless loop .gif of all the views
‚Ä¢ 'T‚Äô scale down current resolution, save a 12 sec. seamless loop .gif

Steps to save a gif/png :
‚Ä¢ go in live/open mode (wait)
‚Ä¢ resize canvas with 6,7,8, or 9 to your desired aspect ratio (wait)
‚Ä¢ press S,G or P to save & download (wait) 
‚Ä¢ enjoy RAUSCH :)

Save & Export GIF for social media sharing:
‚Ä¢ go in live/open mode (wait)
‚Ä¢ press T or G wait for recalculation & download. 
‚Ä¢ enjoy RAUSCH 
‚Ä¢ post on Twitter ;)
__________________________________________________

This token may not work on mobile(!), but it allows exporting .png and .gif (see controls) to enjoy RAUSCH on different displays or mobile. Tested on Mozilla, Chrome, Safari. Created with P5js & p5.createLoop

RAUSCH Generative Token by @grasser_alex 2023

metadata.name: Natural selection #26
metadata.description:
Of all the artworks I have made, this highly conceptual work is my favorite.

This NFT simulates natural selection in a limited population. 

Each individual in the population has their own DNA: a string of 41 letters. In the first generation of the simulation, each individual has completely random DNA.

For each new generation, the two 'fittest' individuals from the previous generation are allowed to reproduce, with their offspring carrying a combination of the DNA of both parents and some random mutations. 

The fitness of an individual is given by the number of letters of their DNA that match the sentence: "Natural selection is anything but random" (a quote from Richard Dawkins).

In total, 40 generations are simulated. The DNA of the fittest individual from each odd-numbered generation is printed.

The probability of a random piece of DNA equals the quote is one in 95^41 ‚âà 10^80, roughly the number of atoms in the universe.

Source code: https://turtletoy.net/turtle/2f92cd6aa3
